Boil a large #pot{} of water for the @quinoa{170%grams}.

Stir in the @beef stock{1%sachet} and quinoa and bring back to the boil.

Cook until the quinoa has doubled in size and the seed has visibly split, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Drain in a #sieve{} and return to the pot, off the heat.

Set aside and cover to keep warm.

While the quinoa cooks, halve the @bell pepper{1}(halved) and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 2cm chunks.

Cut the @tomato{2}(cut into 2cm chunks) into 2cm chunks.

Trim and thinly slice the @scallion{2}(trimmed and thinly sliced).

Add the @mayo{2%sachets}, @harissa paste{1%sachet} and @sweet chilli sauce{1%sachet} to a #small bowl{}.

Mix together until well combined.

Place a large pan over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Season the @Irish beef rump{250%grams} with @harissa spice mix{1%sachet}, @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Once the oil is hot, fry the beef until browned, ~{1-2%minutes} each side for medium-rare.

Cook for another ~{1-2%minutes} on each side if you want it medium and a further ~{1-2%minutes} on each side if you want it well-done.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging. Meat is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Once the beef is cooked to your liking, transfer to a #board{}, cover and allow to rest.

Return the pan to high heat with another drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, fry the pepper and tomatoes until starting to soften, stirring occasionally, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir the drained quinoa into the veg. Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Just before serving, thinly slice the beef.

Divide the quinoa between #bowls{}.

Top with the sliced beef.

Drizzle over the sweet and spicy sauce.

Finish with a scattering of scallion.